    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Life, Stress and the Sixth Grade</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Noam Ross letter responds to July 3 article about pressure on sixth-grade students to prepare for college; asserts school should be opportunity to learn the basics and should not be a race to college (M)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Even for Sixth Graders, College Looms'' (front page, July 3):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Even for Sixth Graders, College Looms'' (front page, July 3):</p>
        <p>The parents and teachers of the students profiled are sending the message that the only goal of the next six years of education is admission to college. School should be an opportunity to learn the basics, explore one's interests and gain a love of knowledge. Instead, it is becoming a race to college. What are these children to do in college if all they know how to do is race?</p>
        <p>NOAM ROSS  Ossining, N.Y., July 3, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a high school senior.</p>
      </block>
